text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%0a!"Needs washed" construction%0a%0a:Author: aryans%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA short introduction to the "needs washed" construction based on the Yale Grammatical Diversity Project%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe needs washed  construction is when the word "needs" is followed by a passive participle verb form like "washed", "fixed", or "cleaned". For example, %0a%0aYour shirt needs washed. %0aThe dryer needs repaired. %0a%0aThis construction isn't in Standard American English, where the same meanings as above would be communicated with the infinitive or gerund form of the verb:%0a%0aYour shirt needs to be washed. (infinitive)%0aThe dryer needs repairing. (gerund)%0a%0aThis construction, according to Murray and Simon (2002), is common in Western Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Ohio, and the Midwestern United States. It may have roots in Scots English. %0a%0aThe same construction can be applied to the words "wants" and "likes". Usually, if a passive participle verb form can be used with "needs", it can be used with "wants". If it can be used with "wants", it can be used with "likes". However, the converses do not necessarily hold. %0a%0aHere's an interesting syntactic property of this construction. If the "needs washed" construction is used with a negation, then the "need" must follow the negation, usually by inserting a "do" auxiliary verb. For example, the first construction is not acceptable, while the second is:%0a%0a*Your shirt needn't washed. %0aYour shirt don't need washed. %0a%0aSource: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/needs-washed%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210420-012403-553640#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Spotted in the wild %0a-> - jjmonroe%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAs noted in the article, this construction is commonly found in Carnegie Mellon's own Western Pennsylvania region. I stumbled across an example of it on campus earlier in the year, and took a photo:%0a%0ahttps://i.imgur.com/p6tFoai.jpg%0ahttps://i.imgur.com/XGYq1bq.jpg%0a%0aThe sticker with contact information for the facilities management person responsible for keeping the mask pocket full says to call if this "needs refilled". It's also interesting to see the sticker using a local construction juxtaposed on top of the fully SAE officially produced and edited COVID information sign.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210420-012403-553640#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)
